# Ownership & Borrowing: A Python Developer's Guide to Rust

## The Core Mental Model Shift

In Python, you rarely think about *who owns* data. In Rust, ownership is the central organizing principle.

```python
# Python: Multiple references to the same object, GC handles cleanup
a = [1, 2, 3]
b = a          # Both point to same list
b.append(4)
print(a)       # [1, 2, 3, 4] - a sees the change!
# Python's GC figures out when to free memory
```

```rust
// Rust: One owner, explicit transfer of ownership
fn main() {
    let a = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let b = a;          // Ownership MOVES to b
    // println!("{:?}", a); // ERROR: a no longer valid!
    println!("{:?}", b);    // Works fine
}
// b goes out of scope here, memory freed automatically - no GC needed
```

---

## Ownership Rules (The Three Laws)

```rust
// Law 1: Each value has exactly ONE owner
// Law 2: When the owner goes out of scope, the value is dropped
// Law 3: There can only be one owner at a time

fn take_ownership(data: Vec<i32>) {
    println!("{:?}", data);
}   // data dropped here

fn main() {
    let numbers = vec![1, 2, 3];
    take_ownership(numbers);
    // println!("{:?}", numbers); // ERROR: moved into function
}
```

**Python analogy:** Imagine if Python worked like this:
```python
# IMAGINARY Python with ownership semantics
numbers = [1, 2, 3]
take_ownership(numbers)
print(numbers)  # NameError: 'numbers' was moved!
```

---

## Borrowing: Temporary Access Without Ownership

```python
# Python: You can pass references freely, no rules enforced
def read_list(data):
    print(data)         # Just reading

def modify_list(data):
    data.append(4)      # Modifying - Python allows this anywhere

my_list = [1, 2, 3]
read_list(my_list)      # my_list still valid
modify_list(my_list)    # my_list still valid
read_list(my_list)      # Prints [1, 2, 3, 4]
# Python has no way to PREVENT modify_list from mutating your data
```

```rust
// Rust: Borrowing with explicit rules enforced at compile time

fn read_vec(data: &Vec<i32>) {        // & means "borrow, read-only"
    println!("{:?}", data);
    // data.push(4);  // ERROR: cannot mutate through immutable reference
}

fn modify_vec(data: &mut Vec<i32>) {  // &mut means "borrow, read-write"
    data.push(4);
}

fn main() {
    let mut numbers = vec![1, 2, 3];

    read_vec(&numbers);       // Lend immutably
    modify_vec(&mut numbers); // Lend mutably
    read_vec(&numbers);       // Prints [1, 2, 3, 4]
    // numbers still owned here, dropped at end of main
}
```

---

## The Borrowing Rules (Preventing Data Races at Compile Time)

```rust
fn main() {
    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3];

    // RULE: Many immutable borrows OR one mutable borrow, never both

    let r1 = &data;
    let r2 = &data;
    println!("{:?} {:?}", r1, r2);  // OK: multiple immutable borrows

    let r3 = &mut data;
    // println!("{:?}", r1);  // ERROR: can't use immutable borrow while
                               // mutable borrow exists
    r3.push(4);                // OK: only r3 exists now
}
```

**Python analogy for why this matters:**
```python
# Python lets this happen - it's a real bug category
import threading

shared_list = [1, 2, 3]

def reader():
    for item in shared_list:    # Reading while...
        print(item)

def writer():
    shared_list.clear()         # ...someone else modifies!
    shared_list.extend([4, 5])

# This is a data race - undefined behavior, hard to debug
# Rust makes this IMPOSSIBLE at compile time
```

---

## `&str` vs `String`: The Core Distinction

This is the most direct answer to your question:

```python
# Python has ONE string type - it handles everything
name = "Alice"              # Interned string literal
greeting = "Hello, " + name # New string object
# Python hides the complexity of where strings live in memory
```

```rust
// Rust has TWO string types because they represent different things

// String: Owned, heap-allocated, growable
let owned: String = String::from("Hello");
let also_owned: String = "Hello".to_string();

// &str: Borrowed reference to string data (a "view")
let borrowed: &str = "Hello";           // Points to binary/static memory
let also_borrowed: &str = &owned;       // Points to owned String's memory
let slice: &str = &owned[0..3];         // Points to part of owned String
```

### Memory Layout Visualization

```
String (owned):
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Stack: ptr ──────────────────────┐  │
│        len: 5                    │  │
│        capacity: 8               │  │  
└──────────────────────────────────┼──┘
                                   ▼
                              Heap: [H][e][l][l][o][ ][ ][ ]

&str (borrowed view):
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Stack: ptr ──────────────────────┐  │
│        len: 5                    │  │
└──────────────────────────────────┼──┘
                                   ▼
                    Points ANYWHERE: heap, stack, binary
                    [H][e][l][l][o]  (no ownership, no allocation)
```

### When to Use Each

```rust
// Use &str for function parameters - accept any string type
fn greet(name: &str) {           // Flexible: accepts &str AND &String
    println!("Hello, {}!", name);
}

// Use String when you need to own or modify the data
fn build_greeting(name: &str) -> String {  // Return owned data
    format!("Hello, {}!", name)
}

fn main() {
    let owned = String::from("Alice");
    let literal = "Bob";

    greet(&owned);    // &String coerces to &str automatically
    greet(literal);   // &str works directly

    let result = build_greeting("Charlie");
    // result is a String we own and can use after this function
}
```

### The Python Equivalent (Closest Analogy)

```python
# &str ≈ a memoryview or read-only slice - a VIEW into existing data
data = bytearray(b"Hello, World")
view = memoryview(data)[0:5]    # View into data, no copy
# view doesn't own the memory, data does

# String ≈ a regular str or bytearray - owns its data
owned = bytearray(b"Hello")     # Owns its memory

# But Python's analogy breaks down because:
# 1. Python strings are immutable, Rust's String is mutable
# 2. Python hides all memory management
# 3. Python can't express "this reference must not outlive its source"
```

---

## Lifetimes: The Part Python Has No Analogy For

```rust
// Rust must ensure borrowed references don't outlive their source
// This is what lifetimes express

fn longest<'a>(x: &'a str, y: &'a str) -> &'a str {
    if x.len() > y.len() { x } else { y }
}

// The 'a says: "the returned reference lives as long as 
// the SHORTER of x and y's lifetimes"

// Python equivalent would be returning a reference to a local variable
// Python: totally fine (GC keeps it alive)
// Rust: compile error if the source might be dropped first
```

```rust
// This is the bug Rust prevents:
fn dangling() -> &str {
    let s = String::from("hello");
    &s          // ERROR: s will be dropped, reference would dangle!
}               // s dropped here

// Python equivalent works because GC keeps object alive:
def not_dangling():
    s = "hello"
    return s    # Python: fine, GC keeps string alive via reference count
```

---

## Summary Table

| Concept | Python | Rust |
|---------|--------|------|
| Memory management | GC / reference counting | Ownership system |
| Multiple references | Always allowed | Immutable: many OK, Mutable: only one |
| Owned string | `str` (everything is owned) | `String` |
| Borrowed string view | `memoryview` (rough analogy) | `&str` |
| Mutation prevention | Convention only | Enforced by compiler |
| Use-after-free bugs | Impossible (GC) | Impossible (ownership) |
| Data races | Possible (runtime) | Impossible (compile time) |

The key insight: **Rust moves Python's runtime safety guarantees to compile time, with zero runtime cost.** The `&str`/`String` distinction exists because Rust needs to know *who is responsible for freeing memory* — something Python's GC handles invisibly but at a performance cost.

